We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The sudden-onset severe headache and limited neck motion suggest a subarachnoid hemorrhage. The most likely responsible vessel is the anterior cerebral artery, which supplies the anterior portion of the brain. The maxillary artery supplies the midface and cranial structures, while the internal carotid artery supplies the anterior portion of the brain but causes a different type of headache. The posterior cerebral artery supplies the posterior portion of the brain.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The sudden onset, severe throbbing headache suggests a subarachnoid hemorrhage (SAH). Among the options, only the anterior cerebral artery directly branches off the internal carotid artery and is responsible for blood supply to the frontal lobe which may cause a headache. SAH is commonly caused by ruptured aneurysms in the anterior circulation, specifically in the anterior communicating and anterior cerebral arteries.

The most common cause of SAH is a ruptured aneurysm, which occurs most commonly at the branching points of the circle of Willis. Among the options, the anterior cerebral artery directly branches off the circle of Willis and is therefore the most likely vessel responsible for this patient's condition.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The sudden onset of severe throbbing headache with limited neck motion and a smoking history suggest a subarachnoid hemorrhage. The most common vessel responsible for this condition is the anterior communicating artery, which directly branches off the anterior cerebral artery (option A). The maxillary artery (option B) supplies blood to the maxilla and surrounding structures, the internal carotid artery (option C) supplies blood to the brain, and the posterior cerebral artery (option D) supplies the occipital lobe and part of the temporal lobe of the brain. None of these vessels are directly involved in subarachnoid hemorrhage.
